sols:
Let

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}e_n(x)=e^{2\pi{}inx}\end{align*}

so that we want $c_i$ such that

\begin{align*}x=\sum_{i=-\infty}^\infty{}c_ie_i(x).\end{align*}

From
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH307/December_2010/Question_06_(a)/Hint_1}{Hint
1} (and setting L=1) we have that $e_n$ are orthogonal i.e.,

\begin{align*}\int_0^1e_n(x)\overline{e_m}(x)\textrm{d}x=\begin{cases}
1,\qquad{}n=m\\
0,\qquad{}n\neq{}m
\end{cases}\end{align*}

where the overbar indicates the complex conjugate

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}\overline{e_n}(x)=e^{-2\pi{}inx}.\end{align*}

We can get the coefficients of $x$ using this orthogonality. Take the
inner product with each $e_{n}(x)$

\begin{align*}\langle e_{n},x \rangle = \sum_{i=-\infty}^{\infty} c_{i} \langle e_{n},e_{i} \rangle = c_{n} \langle e_{n},e_{n} \rangle =c_{n}\end{align*}

\begin{align*}c_{n} = \int_{0}^{1} e^{-2\pi inx}xdx.\end{align*}

If $n\neq 0,$ we use integration by parts\begin{align*}\int udv=uv-\int vdu\end{align*} with
$u = x$, $dv = e^{-2\pi inx}dx$ to obtain

\begin{align*}
c_{n} &= \left [\frac{x}{-2\pi in} e^{-2\pi inx} \right ]^{1}_{0} + \int_{0}^{1} \frac{1}{2\pi in} e^{-2\pi inx}dx \\
&= \left [-\frac{x}{2\pi in} e^{-2\pi inx} - \frac{1}{4\pi^{2} i^{2}n^{2}} e^{-2\pi inx} \right ]^{1}_{0} \\
&= \left [-\frac{x}{2\pi in} e^{-2\pi inx} + \frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}} e^{-2\pi inx} \right ]^{1}_{0} \\
&= \left [\left(\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}}-\frac{x}{2\pi in} \right) e^{-2\pi inx} \right ]^{1}_{0} \\
&= \left [\left(\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}}-\frac{1}{2\pi in} \right) e^{-2\pi in(1)} \right ]-\left [\left(\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}}-0 \right) e^{-2\pi in(0)} \right ] \\
&= \left(\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}}-\frac{1}{2\pi in} \right) e^{-2\pi in}- \frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}} \\
&= \left(\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}}-\frac{1}{2\pi in} \right) (1)- \frac{1}{4\pi^{2}n^{2}} \\
&=-\frac{1}{2\pi in}\\
&=\frac{i}{2\pi{}n}\end{align*}

Here we see the importance of having $n\neq0$, otherwise the coefficient
diverges using this formula. If \emph{n = 0},

\begin{align*}c_{0} = \int_{0}^{1} f(x)dx = \left [\frac{1}{2}x^{2} \right ]^{1}_{0}= \frac{1}{2}\end{align*}

Therefore, we have all the coefficients for the series.

hints:
Recall that the functions

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}e^{2\pi{}inx/L}\end{align*}

are an orthogonal basis for square integrable functions, i.e.

\begin{align*}\int_0^Le^{2\pi{}inx/L}e^{-2\pi{}imx/L}\textrm{d}x=\begin{cases}
L,\qquad{}n=m\\
0,\qquad{}n\neq{}m
\end{cases}\end{align*}

How can we use this orthogonality to get the coefficients in the series?
